@NODE "INTRO" "PicSort2"
@NEXT "REQUIRE"
@PREV "MAIN"
@TOC "MAIN"
1. Introduction

   PicSort is an utility to sort images. At
   least this is it's main purpose.

   Due to many user requests, I applicated
   a script system. That makes PicSort
   highly configurable and flexible.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "REQUIRE" "PicSort2"
@NEXT "INSTALL"
@PREV "INTRO"
@TOC "MAIN"
2. Requirements

   At least you need an AMIGA computer
   to use PicSort.

   OS3 is required for the datatype
   system of the internal picture viewer.

   PicSort uses the TRITON library
   and the TRITONREXX library, both
   supplied within the PicSort distri-
   bution.

   I recommend to install the complete
   TRITON system, available from the
   AmiNet (dev/gui/triXXXusr.lha)


@ENDNODE

@NODE "INSTALL" "PicSort2"
@NEXT "USE"
@PREV "REQUIRE"
@TOC "MAIN"
3. Installation

   To install PicSort to your system,
   simply drag the whole drawer named
   PicSort to a place on your hard-
   disk.

   PicSort is written in ARexx, so you
   have to run SYS:System/RexxMast.
   This is normally done within your
   Startup-Sequence. If not, start
   RexxMast by hand before running
   PicSort.

   All related files are stored in
   the PicSort drawer, so you can de-
   install PicSort easily by deleting
   this drawer.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "USE" "PicSort2"
@NEXT "PREFS"
@PREV "INSTALL"
@TOC "MAIN"
4. How to use PicSort

   Simply double-click on the PicSort
   icon :-)

   Then the start window opens and
   waits for your actions:

   Press the Prefs button (or type 'P')
   to configure PicSort.

   The Sort Pictures button directly
   leads to the main window.

   I think, the About and Quit button
   speak for themselves...


@ENDNODE

@NODE "PREFS" "PicSort2"
@NEXT "BUTTONS"
@PREV "USE"
@TOC "MAIN"
4.1. Prefs

   PicSort assigns directories on
   your harddisk (or any other of
   your devices) to buttons in its
   main window.

   The window is separated in 4
   groups:

      4.1.1. Buttons

      4.1.2. File handling

      4.1.3. Viewer

      4.1.4. Load/Save/Use/Cancel



@ENDNODE

@NODE "BUTTONS" "PicSort2"
@NEXT "FILE"
@PREV "PREFS"
@TOC "MAIN"
4.1.1. Buttons

   The buttons group in the prefs
   window can be used to define the
   buttons (left string gadget) and
   assign the paths (right string
   gadget)

   Using the New button, you can
   define a new button, Delete erases
   the current selected button,
   and to sort the button definitions,
   you might use the Up and Down
   buttons.

   If you want keyboard shortcuts for
   the buttons, place an underline
   (= '_') in front of the letter you
   want to use as shortcut.

   Example:
      _Amiga

   makes 'Amiga' become the button
   text and the key 'A' becomes the
   related shortcut.




@ENDNODE

@NODE "FILE" "PicSort2"
@NEXT "VIEW"
@PREV "BUTTONS"
@TOC "MAIN"
4.1.2. File handling:

   With the file handling group,
   you can define, what PicSort does
   to the images.
   The Method gadget specifies, wether
   PicSort copies the files, or moves
   them to their new directory.

   Related files are files, that
   belong to the image. This
   might be icons, descriptions,
   thumbnails or anything else.
   They have the same name as the
   picture with an additional suffix.

   Example:
     foo.jpg         (the image)
   might have the related files
     foo.jpg.info    (the related icon)
     foo.jpg.readme  (a readme file)
     foo.jpg.thb     (a thumbnail)

   If you want PicSort to act on
   the related files, too, you have to
   activate the related files checkbox
   and to define the suffixes.

   Use the Add and Delete gadgets in
   the File handling group for this.




@ENDNODE

@NODE "VIEW" "PicSort2"
@NEXT "LOAD"
@PREV "FILE"
@TOC "MAIN"
4.1.3. Viewer

   The Viewer group is made to con-
   figure the external picture viewer.

   If PicSort should show the picture
   automatically, check the Auto view
   checkbox.

   To define an external viewer, enter
   its name to the Viewer string gadget.

   The picture name is automatically
   appended to the viewer name, when
   the viewer is started.

   I recommend MysticView, (c) Timm
   S. Mueller, available from the
   AmiNet or

http://tek.flynet.de/binarydistillery/index.html

   as it is very easy to configure and
   intends to be the best picture viewer
   available for the Amiga.

   Additional arguments for the viewer
   can be entered in the arguments
   string gadget.


   To configure MysticView, start it,

   make all your settings (I suggest
   to set 'Options/Quit after last
   Picture' on) and save the Presets
   as "ENVARC:MysticView_PicSort.prefs"

   Then enter the following line in the
   viewer arguments string gadget:

   PRESETFILE=ENVARC:MysticView_PicSort.prefs

   Then PicSort uses MysticView as
   external viewer, and MysticView
   uses the settings you want it to
   use for PicSort only.

   If you want PicSort to use its
   internal datatypes-viewer, check
   the Use internal first checkbox.




@ENDNODE

@NODE "LOAD" "PicSort2"
@NEXT "MAINWIN"
@PREV "VIEW"
@TOC "MAIN"
4.1.4. Load/Save/Use/Cancel

   Use the Load button to load a prefs
   file.

   The Save button lets you specify a
   filename and saves the prefs.

   The Use button closes the prefs
   window and passes your prefs to
   PicSort.

   And the Cancel button closes the
   prefs window without changing the
   preferences.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "MAINWIN" "PicSort2"
@NEXT "SCRIPTS"
@PREV "LOAD"
@TOC "MAIN"
4.2. The Main window

   Use the Select images button to
   select the files you want to sort.
   The file requester ignores related
   files by default.

   The Exit button returns you to the
   start window.

   Once PicSort has read the picture
   list you selected, it shows the
   first picture, if you enabled Auto
   show, or it waits for your action.

   You can change the file name, the
   date and the file commen. Refer to
   the Amiga DOS command SetDate for
   how to enter the file date.

   If you want to view the image, use
   one of the View buttons.
   The View internal button only works
   with DataTypes installed, and the
   View external button needs an
   external viewer to be configured.

   Once you have decided, what to do
   with the image file, use the
   Skip button to move on to the next
   image, or the Delete button to
   delete the image (and its related
   files!!!)

   But if you want to keep the image,
   use one of the buttons in the
   Sort buttons window to move / copy
   the image file and its related
   files to the directory assigned
   to the button.

   See Scripts for description of the
   Scripts button group.


@ENDNODE

@NODE "SCRIPTS" "PicSort2"
@NEXT "PROBS"
@PREV "MAINWIN"
@TOC "MAIN"
@ENDNODE

@NODE "PROBS" "PicSort2"
@NEXT "COPY"
@PREV "SCRIPTS"
@TOC "MAIN"
6. Known problems

   I haven't one :-)

   But if you have problems while using
   PicSort, let me know about.

   You might enable a debug mode by
   putting brackets around the
   Tool Type CONSOLE=NIL: in the PicSort
   icon.
   Then a debug window opens. If you
   contact me, please send me the output
   from this window, especially error
   messages.

   Sometimes PicSort can't open the
   Button window. This can be caused
   by too many button definitions, if
   the screen is too small. Try to
   reduce the number of buttons then.


